05022nam a22007935i 9780231542289DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018041851  a97802315422897 a10.7312/stre179822doi  a(DE-B1597)526848  a(OCoLC)1060181470  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1995.9.C546bS769 2019 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43012231 aStreet, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChromatic Modernity :bColor, Cinema, and Media of the 1920s /cJoshua Yumibe, Sarah Street. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b120 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm and Culture Series00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. Color Standards and the Industrial Field of Film -- t2. Advertising, Fashion, and Color -- t3. Synthetic Dreams: Expanded Spaces of Cinema -- t4. Color in the Art and Avant-Garde of the 1920s -- t5. Chromatic Hybridity -- t6. Color and the Coming of Sound -- t7. Conclusion -- tNOTES -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe era of silent film, long seen as black and white, has been revealed in recent scholarship as bursting with color. Yet the 1920s remain thought of as a transitional decade between early cinema and the rise of Technicolor—despite the fact that new color technologies used in film, advertising, fashion, and industry reshaped cinema and consumer culture. In Chromatic Modernity, Sarah Street and Joshua Yumibe provide a revelatory history of how the use of color in film during the 1920s played a key role in creating a chromatically vibrant culture.Focusing on the final decade of silent film, Street and Yumibe portray the 1920s as a pivotal and profoundly chromatic period of cosmopolitan exchange, collaboration, and experimentation in and around cinema. Chromatic Modernity explores contemporary debates over color’s artistic, scientific, philosophical, and educational significance. It examines a wide range of European and American films, including Opus 1 (1921), L’Inhumaine (1923), Die Nibelungen (1924), The Phantom of the Opera (1925), The Lodger (1927), Napoléon (1927), and Dracula (1932). A comprehensive, comparative study that situates film among developments in art, color science, and industry, Chromatic Modernity reveals the role of color cinema in forging new ways of looking at and experiencing the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aColor in advertisingxHistory. 0aColor motion picturesxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aYumibe, Joshua, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2019z9783110605785oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishz978311061001708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/stre1798240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231542289423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231542289.jpg  a978-3-11-061001-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065195-9  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_MUAR  